  "prompt": "How do I solve cubic ecuations if I am only allowed to use windows calculator and a piece of paper?",
  "response": "Solving cubic equations using only a Windows Calculator and a piece of paper can be challenging, but it's definitely possible with some patience and careful calculation. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you through the process:\n\n### Step 1: Understanding the Cubic Equation\nA general cubic equation can be written as:\n\\[ ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0 \\]\n\n### Step 2: Simplifying the Equation\nTo simplify calculations, we can eliminate the \\( bx^2 \\) term by making a substitution. Let:\n\\[ x = y - \\frac{b}{3a} \\]\n\nThis transforms the equation into a \"depressed\" cubic equation:\n\\[ y^3 + py + q = 0 \\]\nwhere:\n\\[ p = \\frac{3ac - b^2}{3a^2} \\]\n\\[ q = \\frac{2b^3 - 9abc + 27a^2d}{27a^3} \\]\n\n### Step 3: Using the Calculator to Find \\( p \\) and \\( q \\)\n1. Calculate \\( p \\):\n   - Calculate \\( 3ac \\)\n   - Calculate \\( b^2 \\)\n   - Subtract \\( b^2 \\) from \\( 3ac \\)\n   - Divide the result by \\( 3a^2 \\)\n\n2. Calculate \\( q \\):\n   - Calculate \\( b^3 \\)\n   - Calculate \\( 9abc \\)\n   - Calculate \\( 27a^2d \\)\n   - Multiply \\( b^3 \\) by 2\n   - Subtract \\( 9abc \\) from \\( 2b^3 \\)\n   - Add \\( 27a^2d \\)\n   - Divide the result by \\( 27a^3 \\)\n\n### Step 4: Solving the Depressed Cubic Equation\nTo solve \\( y^3 + py + q = 0 \\), we use Cardano's Formula. We need to find the roots of:\n\\[ y = \\sqrt[3]{-\\frac{q}{2} + \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3}} + \\sqrt[3]{-\\frac{q}{2} - \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3}} \\]\n\n1. Calculate \\( \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3 \\):\n   - Divide \\( p \\) by 3\n   - Calculate the cube of the result\n\n2. Calculate \\( \\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 \\):\n   - Divide \\( q \\) by 2\n   - Calculate the square of the result\n\n3. Calculate \\( \\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3 \\):\n   - Add the results from steps 1 and 2\n\n4. Calculate \\( \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3} \\):\n   - Find the square root of the result from step 3\n\n5. Calculate \\( -\\frac{q}{2} + \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3} \\):\n   - Divide \\( q \\) by 2 and negate the result\n   - Add the result from step 4\n\n6. Calculate \\( -\\frac{q}{2} - \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{q}{2}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{p}{3}\\right)^3} \\):\n   - Divide \\( q \\) by 2 and negate the result\n   - Subtract the result from step 4\n\n7. Calculate the cube roots:\n   - Find the cube root of the result from step 5\n   - Find the cube root of the result from step 6\n\n8. Add the two cube roots to get \\( y \\):\n   - Add the results from steps 7\n\n### Step 5: Finding \\( x \\)\nOnce you have \\( y \\), convert back to \\( x \\):\n\\[ x = y - \\frac{b}{3a} \\]\n\n### Step 6: Verifying the Solution\nSubstitute \\( x \\) back into the original cubic equation to ensure it satisfies the equation.\n\n### Example\nLet's solve \\( x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 6 = 0 \\):\n\n1. \\( a = 1 \\), \\( b = -6 \\), \\( c = 11 \\), \\( d = -6 \\)\n\n2. Simplify to depressed form:\n   - \\( p = \\frac{3(1)(11) - (-6)^2}{3(1)^2} = \\frac{33 - 36}{3} = -1 \\)\n   - \\( q = \\frac{2(-6)^3 - 9(1)(-6)(11) + 27(1)^2(-6)}{27(1)^3} = \\frac{-432 + 594 - 162}{27} = 0 \\)\n\n3. Solve the depressed cubic \\( y^3 - y = 0 \\):\n   - \\( y(y^2 - 1) = 0 \\)\n   - \\( y(y - 1)(y + 1) = 0 \\)\n   - \\( y = 0 \\), \\( y = 1 \\), \\( y = -1 \\)\n\n4. Convert back to \\( x \\):\n   - For \\( y = 0 \\): \\( x = 0 - \\frac{-6}{3(1)} = 2 \\)\n   - For \\( y = 1 \\): \\( x = 1 - \\frac{-6}{3(1)} = 3 \\)\n   - For \\( y = -1 \\): \\( x = -1 - \\frac{-6}{3(1)} = 1 \\)\n\n5. Verify:\n   - \\( 2^3 - 6(2^2) + 11(2) - 6 = 8 - 24 + 22 - 6 = 0 \\)\n   - \\( 3^3 - 6(3^2) + 11(3) - 6 = 27 - 54 + 33 - 6 = 0 \\)\n   - \\( 1^3 - 6(1^2) + 11(1) - 6 = 1 - 6 + 11 - 6 = 0 \\)\n\nThus, the solutions are \\( x = 2 \\), \\( x = 3 \\), and \\( x = 1 \\).\n\nThis method requires careful calculation and attention to detail, but it's feasible with just a Windows Calculator and a piece of paper.",
